The Presidential couple then planned a meeting with the Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will reach its climax with the ceremony at which Obama takes the prestigious award.
He receives this as the fourth U.S. president, but only as the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes the prize.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forgets to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the Golmedaille, the diploma and the check over ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, at which the Prime Minister and 250 invited guests will be present in addition to Norway’s King and Queen.
Obama was very reluctant about the price from the start.
For example, he stated that he felt that he did not fully deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not only for him, but for all who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this was a "call to action".
