The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-long animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with silk claws, and a long tail.
If the species lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, according to Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund Confirms Theories About Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts don’t necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current theory, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the allocation of these ancient dinosaurs is usually controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the squirrels split into their three main lines of development: the meat-eating theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor and also the birds, which were known as the "long-tailed squirrels" the squirrels and the squirrels.
According to analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, as they also have the descendants of theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacks and lightweight bones, it is likely that the common ancestor of both groups had produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the squirrels first appeared there.
As a result, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all the continents that were still a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods, speaks for this.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are contradictions as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonner paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted image could emerge, because in South America there are just so many primitive dino fossils preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to find.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant landworms of the Middle Ages is still enigmatic.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying squirrels and numerous other squirrels.
Towards the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread throughout the world and developed many new species, while the kinship at the border from the Trias to the Jurassic extinction.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but not the other reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
However, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halfed a group of animals to bloom, which had also evolved in the Triassic and has since been tempted by a shadow presence: the mammals.
