The insane thoughts and hallucinations met in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
Exceptional conditions can cause any person to lose the reality relationship for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers estimate that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example, by a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But there remains a mystery as to how the disorder of the neuronal system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at first over many years.
Environmental influences also play a role – stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychoses as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
