Whether fraudulent images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and carriers for ten years, last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical accompaniments of psychoses, but also of astonishingly many other diseases.
These include, in addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and skull brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to boxes, are composed of memory contents that are usually retained.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or insufficiently inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also attraction, stress, love resentment or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lifetime.
