A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of desperation
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from atrial fibrillation, they are most likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then under-employed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, she often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls dad since she can think is not her dead father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same brain regions that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Each experience," says Kasten, " takes place in the brain, reality takes place there.
