Even nocturnal dream images value boxing as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations also as a special ability.
The boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly conscious world, imaginary experience is mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, Professor in Heidelberg and Head of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also carries positive, creative - madness is also a work of art from despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroide form of experience, a special form of dreamically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and that he cannot distinguish from the waking state afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in patients with polyradiculitis who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self- and world-loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening reality situation with his own, imaginary world detached from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of border state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the reality is presented in the imagination.
An intense form of foundation and devotion in a situation that is unbearable in itself, which allows us humans to have their own capacity to subside in nothingness of loss of consciousness.
