He goes on completely in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for clauses from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of mental travel are still very clear to me after years and in extraordinarily detailed detail.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience explodes the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug noise show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the box psychologist summarizes, “can lead to a distortion of what we call reality.”
An experience that can be quite enriching.
