Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then, and as is now the case with the ESP stability control, the emergency braking assistance systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, for the rest of the vehicles a leave period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union is intended to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to their operation, these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical braking maneuver which the system detects on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident before the collision no longer entered the brake pedal and half of them had not fully braked.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car places in the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents – one expects one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury – once so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time already exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver reacts, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
