Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an assessor has to assess the damage caused and the cost of repair.
No accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of the reviewers use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from the manufacturers to process it thereafter and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are made with their products.
The other two companies that compete with the tool market for reviewing and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Vel<0xC3><0xA1>zquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each providing the information in a different format.
Furthermore, the amount of data to be processed is growing, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and motorizations have come on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car arrives on the market, the business starts to work.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be cataloged and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week, if the process proceeds quickly.
When it comes to a less common car, it can take up to three or four months.Audatex currently has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the fleet of vehicles driving on the roads, it is over 99%.
Audatex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) distributed for the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, and each of them specializes in certain brands.
